[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-filter-p02] Standard low pass Inverse Chebyshev filter design creates an equi-ripple stop band beginning from a normalized value of 1 rad/sec to $\infty$ .
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-filter-p02] However, some design requirements do not need an equi-ripple pass band at the high frequencies.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-filter-p02] A standard full-equi-ripple Inverse Chebyshev filter for this application would result in an over designed filter.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-filter-p02] Constricting the equi-ripple to a defined percentage of the stop band creates a more efficient design, reducing the size of the filter and potentially eliminating one or two components, which is useful in maximizing board space efficiency and minimizing production costs for mass produced items.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-filter-p02] Inverse Chebyshev filters with constricted stop band ripple are synthesized in exactly the same process as standard a inverse Chebyshev.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-filter-p02] A constricted ripple Chebyshev is designed with an inverted $\varepsilon$ , $\varepsilon ^{2}=1/(10^{(\gamma /10)}-1)$ where $\gamma$ is the stop band attenuation in dB, the poles and zeros of the designed constricted ripple Chebyshev filter are inverted, and the cut-off attenuation is set.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-filter-p02] Since standard Chebyshev equations will not work with constricted ripple design, the cut-off attenuation must be set using the process described in the Elliptic Hourglass design.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-filter-p02] Below are the |S11| and |S12| scattering parameters for a 7 pole constricted ripple Inverse Chebyshev filter with 3dB cut-off attenuation.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-filter-p02] The constricted ripple example above is intentionally kept simple by keeping the cut-off attenuation equal to the pass band ripple attenuation, omitting optional transmission zeros, and using an odd order that does not potentially require even order modification.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-filter-p02] When including stop band transmission zeros, it is import to remember that the roots of $dK(s)/ds)_{num}$ will include stop band maxima with $\omega >1$ .
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-filter-p02] These roots should not be included in the pass band minima used in the computations..
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-filter-p02] Since $\varepsilon ^{2}$ may be used to set the cut-off attenuation in $G(s)$ , the step 5 $K(s)$ target values may be made with respect to 1.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-filter-p02] The target values in step 5 may be calculated using the expression for $|K(j\omega )|$ obtainable from the equations above.
