[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-nodes] In numerical analysis, **Chebyshev nodes** (also called **Chebyshev points** or a **Chebyshev grid**) are a set of specific algebraic numbers used as nodes for polynomial interpolation and numerical integration.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-nodes] They are the projection of a set of equispaced points on the unit circle onto the real interval $[-1,1]$ , the circle's diameter.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-nodes] The ⁠ n ⁠ *Chebyshev nodes of the first kind*, also called the **Chebyshev–Gauss nodes** or **Chebyshev zeros**, are the zeros of a Chebyshev polynomial of the first kind, ⁠ $T_{n}$ ⁠.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-nodes] The corresponding ⁠ $n+1$ ⁠ *Chebyshev nodes of the second kind*, also called the **Chebyshev–Lobatto nodes** or **Chebyshev extrema**, are the extrema of ⁠ $T_{n}$ ⁠, which are also the zeros of a Chebyshev polynomial of the second kind, ⁠ $U_{n-1}$ ⁠, along with the two endpoints of the interval.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-nodes] Both types of numbers are commonly referred to as *Chebyshev nodes* or *Chebyshev points* in literature.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-nodes] They are named after 19th century Russian mathematician Pafnuty Chebyshev, who first introduced Chebyshev polynomials.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-nodes] Unlike some other interpolation nodes, the Chebyshev nodes "nest": the existing nodes are retained when doubling the number of nodes, reducing computation for each grid refinement by half.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-nodes] Polynomial interpolants constructed from Chebyshev nodes minimize the effect of Runge's phenomenon.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-nodes] They can be easily converted to a representation as a weighted sum of Chebyshev polynomials using the fast Fourier transform.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-nodes] This is the projection of ⁠ $2n$ ⁠ equispaced points on the unit circle onto the interval ⁠ $[-1,1]$ ⁠, the circle's diameter.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-nodes] These points are also the roots of ⁠ $T_{n}$ ⁠, the Chebyshev polynomial of the first kind with degree ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-nodes] This is also the projection of ⁠ $2n$ ⁠ equispaced points on the unit circle onto ⁠ $[-1,1]$ ⁠, this time including the endpoints of the interval, each of which is only the projection of one point on the circle rather than two.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-nodes] These points are also the extrema of ⁠ $T_{n}$ ⁠ in ⁠ $[-1,1]$ ⁠, the places where it takes the value ⁠ $\pm 1$ ⁠.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-nodes] The interior points among the nodes, not including the endpoints, are also the zeros of ⁠ $U_{n-1}$ ⁠, a Chebyshev polynomial of the second kind, a rescaling of the derivative of ⁠ $T_{n}$ ⁠.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-nodes] Both kinds of nodes are always symmetric about zero, the midpoint of the interval.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-nodes] While these sets are sorted by ascending values, the defining formulas given above generate the Chebyshev nodes in reverse order from the greatest to the smallest.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-nodes] The Chebyshev nodes are important in approximation theory because they form a particularly good set of nodes for polynomial interpolation.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-nodes] Given a function *f* on the interval $[-1,+1]$ and n points $x_{1},x_{2},\ldots ,x_{n},$ in that interval, the interpolation polynomial is that unique polynomial $P_{n-1}$ of degree at most $n-1$ which has value $f(x_{i})$ at each point $x_{i}$ .
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-nodes] This product is a *monic* polynomial of degree n.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-nodes] It may be shown that the maximum absolute value (maximum norm) of any such polynomial is bounded from below by 21−*n*.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-nodes] This bound is attained by the scaled Chebyshev polynomials 21−*n* *T**n*, which are also monic.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-nodes] Some applications for interpolation nodes, such as the design of equally terminated passive Chebyshev filters, cannot use even-order Chebyshev nodes directly due to the lack of a root at 0.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-nodes] The modified even-order nodes now include zero twice.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] The **Chebyshev polynomials** are two sequences of orthogonal polynomials related to the cosine and sine functions, notated as $T_{n}(x)$ and $U_{n}(x)$ .
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] That these expressions define polynomials in $\cos \theta$ is not obvious at first sight but can be shown using de Moivre's formula (see below).
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] The Chebyshev polynomials *Tn* are polynomials with the largest possible leading coefficient whose absolute value on the interval [−1, 1] is bounded by 1.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] They are also the "extremal" polynomials for many other properties.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] In 1952, Cornelius Lanczos showed that the Chebyshev polynomials are important in approximation theory for the solution of linear systems; the roots of *Tn*(*x*), which are also called *Chebyshev nodes*, are used as matching points for optimizing polynomial interpolation.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] The resulting interpolation polynomial minimizes the problem of Runge's phenomenon and provides an approximation that is close to the best polynomial approximation to a continuous function under the maximum norm, also called the "minimax" criterion.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] This approximation leads directly to the method of Clenshaw–Curtis quadrature.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] These polynomials were named after Pafnuty Chebyshev.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] The letter T is used because of the alternative transliterations of the name *Chebyshev* as *Tchebycheff*, *Tchebyshev* (French) or *Tschebyschow* (German).
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] The Chebyshev polynomials of the first and second kind can be defined as the unique polynomials satisfying $T_{n}(\cos \theta )=\cos(n\theta )\quad$ and $U_{n}(\cos \theta )={\frac {{\sin }{\big (}(n+1)\theta {\big )}}{\sin \theta }},$ for *n* = 0, 1, 2, 3, ….
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] Chebyshev polynomials can also be defined in this form when studying trigonometric polynomials.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] The real part of the other side is a polynomial in $\cos x$ and $\sin x$ , in which all powers of $\sin x$ are even and thus replaceable through the identity $\cos ^{2}x+\sin ^{2}x=1$ .
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] By the same reasoning, $\sin nx$ is the imaginary part of the polynomial, in which all powers of $\sin x$ are odd and thus, if one factor of $\sin x$ is factored out, the remaining factors can be replaced to create a polynomial of degree $n-1$ in $\cos x$ .
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] This relationship is used in the Chebyshev spectral method of solving differential equations.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] where integrals are considered as principal value.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] An explicit form of the Chebyshev polynomial in terms of monomials $\textstyle x^{k}$ can be obtained as follows.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] Chebyshev polynomials of odd order have odd symmetry and therefore contain only odd powers of x .
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] A Chebyshev polynomial of either kind with degree n has n different simple roots, called **Chebyshev roots**, in the interval [−1, 1].
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] The roots of the Chebyshev polynomial of the first kind are sometimes called Chebyshev nodes because they are used as *nodes* in polynomial interpolation.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] Thus these polynomials have only two finite critical values, the defining property of Shabat polynomials.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] The derivatives of the polynomials can be less than straightforward.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] Since $T_{m}(x)$ is divisible by x if m is odd, it follows that $T_{mn}(x)$ is divisible by $T_{n}(x)$ if m is odd.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] Both $T_{n}$ and $U_{n}$ form a sequence of orthogonal polynomials.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] These orthogonality properties follow from the fact that the Chebyshev polynomials solve the Chebyshev differential equations ${\begin{aligned}(1-x^{2})T_{n}''-xT_{n}'+n^{2}T_{n}&=0,\\[1ex](1-x^{2})U_{n}''-3xU_{n}'+n(n+2)U_{n}&=0,\end{aligned}}$ which are Sturm–Liouville differential equations.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] It is a general feature of such differential equations that there is a distinguished orthonormal set of solutions.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] For any given $n\geq 1$ , among the polynomials of degree n with leading coefficient 1 (monic polynomials): $f(x)={\frac {1}{2^{n-1}}}T_{n}(x)$ is the one of which the maximal absolute value on the interval [−1, 1] is minimal.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] Let's assume that $w_{n}(x)$ is a polynomial of degree n with leading coefficient 1 with maximal absolute value on the interval [−1, 1] less than 1 / 2*n* − 1.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] From the intermediate value theorem, *fn*(*x*) has at least n roots.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] However, this is impossible, as *fn*(*x*) is a polynomial of degree *n* − 1, so the fundamental theorem of algebra implies it has at most *n* − 1 roots.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] By the equioscillation theorem, among all the polynomials of degree ≤ *n*, the polynomial f minimizes ‖ *f* ‖∞ on [−1, 1] if and only if there are *n* + 2 points −1 ≤ *x*0 < *x*1 < ⋯ < *x**n* + 1 ≤ 1 such that | *f*(*xi*)| = ‖ *f* ‖∞.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] Of course, the null polynomial on the interval [−1, 1] can be approximated by itself and minimizes the ∞-norm.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] Above, however, | *f* | reaches its maximum only *n* + 1 times because we are searching for the best polynomial of degree *n* ≥ 1 (therefore the theorem evoked previously cannot be used).
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] The curves given by *y* = *T**n*(*x*), or equivalently, by the parametric equations *y* = *T**n*(cos *θ*) = cos *nθ*, *x* = cos *θ*, are a special case of Lissajous curves with frequency ratio equal to n.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] This sum is called a **Chebyshev series** or a **Chebyshev expansion**.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] Since a Chebyshev series is related to a Fourier cosine series through a change of variables, all of the theorems, identities, etc. that apply to Fourier series have a Chebyshev counterpart.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] The Chebfun software package supports function manipulation based on their expansion in the Chebyshev basis.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] Consider the Chebyshev expansion of log(1 + *x*).
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] One can find the coefficients *an* either through the application of an inner product or by the discrete orthogonality condition.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] For any N, these approximate coefficients provide an exact approximation to the function at xk with a controlled error between those points.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] The exact coefficients are obtained with *N* = ∞, thus representing the function exactly at all points in [−1,1].
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] The rate of convergence depends on the function and its smoothness.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] The partial sums of: $f(x)=\sum _{n=0}^{\infty }a_{n}T_{n}(x)$ are very useful in the approximation of various functions and in the solution of differential equations (see spectral method).
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] Two common methods for determining the coefficients an are through the use of the inner product as in Galerkin's method and through the use of collocation which is related to interpolation.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] As an interpolant, the N coefficients of the (*N* − 1)st partial sum are usually obtained on the Chebyshev–Gauss–Lobatto points (or Lobatto grid), which results in minimum error and avoids Runge's phenomenon associated with a uniform grid.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] An arbitrary polynomial of degree N can be written in terms of the Chebyshev polynomials of the first kind.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] Polynomials in Chebyshev form can be evaluated using the Clenshaw algorithm.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] Polynomials denoted $C_{n}(x)$ and $S_{n}(x)$ closely related to Chebyshev polynomials are sometimes used.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] Horadam called the polynomials $C_{n}(x)$ **Vieta–Lucas polynomials** and denoted them $v_{n}(x)$ .
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] He called the polynomials $S_{n}(x)$ **Vieta–Fibonacci polynomials** and denoted them $V_{n}(x)$ .
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] All of these polynomials have 1 as their leading coefficient.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] Lists of both sets of polynomials are given in Viète's *Opera Mathematica*, Chapter IX, Theorems VI and VII.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] The Vieta–Lucas and Vieta–Fibonacci polynomials of real argument are, up to a power of i and a shift of index in the case of the latter, equal to Lucas and Fibonacci polynomials *L**n* and *F**n* of imaginary argument.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] When the argument of the Chebyshev polynomial satisfies 2*x* − 1 ∈ [−1, 1] the argument of the shifted Chebyshev polynomial satisfies *x* ∈ [0, 1].
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] Similarly, one can define shifted polynomials for generic intervals [*a*, *b*].
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] Around 1990 the terms "third-kind" and "fourth-kind" came into use in connection with Chebyshev polynomials, although the polynomials denoted by these terms had an earlier development under the name **airfoil polynomials**.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] They coincide with the Dirichlet kernel.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] It is easier to discuss this detail by first examining the factorization of the Vieta-Lucas and Vieta-Fibonacci polynomials.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] The polynomials $\Psi _{n}(x)$ may be referred to as cyclotomic pre-polynomials, since the cyclotomic polynomials can be obtained from them via a well-defined mapping.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] An obvious property of the mapping $P_{n}(x)\rightarrow x^{n}P_{n}{\left(x+{\frac {1}{x}}\right)}$ applicable to any polynomial $P_{n}(x)$ of degree n is that it maps the product of two or more polynomials to the product of the images of the individual polynomials.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] From the irreducibility of the polynomials $\Phi _{n}(x)$ it follows that the polynomials $\Psi _{n}(x)$ are also irreducible.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] Some applications rely on Chebyshev polynomials but may be unable to accommodate the lack of a root at zero, which rules out the use of standard Chebyshev polynomials for these kinds of applications.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] Even order Chebyshev filter designs using equally terminated passive networks are an example of this.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] However, even order Chebyshev polynomials may be modified to move the lowest roots down to zero while still maintaining the desirable Chebyshev equi-ripple effect.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] Such modified polynomials contain two roots at zero, and may be referred to as even order modified Chebyshev polynomials.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] Even order modified Chebyshev polynomials may be created from the Chebyshev nodes in the same manner as standard Chebyshev polynomials.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] In the case of even order modified Chebyshev polynomials, the even order modified Chebyshev nodes are used to construct the even order modified Chebyshev polynomials.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] For example, the 4th order Chebyshev polynomial from the example above is $X^{4}-X^{2}+.125$ , which by inspection contains no roots of zero.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/chebyshev-polynomials] Creating the polynomial from the even order modified Chebyshev nodes creates a 4th order even order modified Chebyshev polynomial of $X^{4}-.828427X^{2}$ , which by inspection contains two roots at zero, and may be used in applications requiring roots at zero.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/clenshaw-algorithm] In numerical analysis, the **Clenshaw algorithm**, also called **Clenshaw summation**, is a recursive method to evaluate a linear combination of Chebyshev polynomials.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/clenshaw-algorithm] The method was published by Charles William Clenshaw in 1955.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/clenshaw-algorithm] It is a generalization of Horner's method for evaluating a linear combination of monomials.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/clenshaw-algorithm] It generalizes to more than just Chebyshev polynomials; it applies to any class of functions that can be defined by a three-term recurrence relation.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/clenshaw-algorithm] The algorithm is most useful when $\phi _{k}(x)$ are functions that are complicated to compute directly, but $\alpha _{k}(x)$ and $\beta _{k}(x)$ are particularly simple.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/clenshaw-algorithm] In the most common applications, $\alpha (x)$ does not depend on k , and $\beta$ is a constant that depends on neither x nor k .
[src:chebyshev-approximation/clenshaw-algorithm] Note that this computation makes no direct reference to the functions $\phi _{k}(x)$ .
[src:chebyshev-approximation/clenshaw-algorithm] See Fox and Parker for more information and stability analyses.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/clenshaw-algorithm] A particularly simple case occurs when evaluating a polynomial of the form $S(x)=\sum _{k=0}^{n}a_{k}x^{k}.$ The functions are simply ${\begin{aligned}\phi _{0}(x)&=1,\\\phi _{k}(x)&=x^{k}=x\phi _{k-1}(x)\end{aligned}}$ and are produced by the recurrence coefficients $\alpha (x)=x$ and $\beta =0$ .
[src:chebyshev-approximation/clenshaw-algorithm] In this case, the recurrence formula to compute the sum is $b_{k}(x)=a_{k}+xb_{k+1}(x)$ and, in this case, the sum is simply $S(x)=a_{0}+xb_{1}(x)=b_{0}(x),$ which is exactly the usual Horner's method.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/clenshaw-algorithm] Clenshaw summation is extensively used in geodetic applications.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/clenshaw-algorithm] A simple application is summing the trigonometric series to compute the meridian arc distance on the surface of an ellipsoid.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/clenshaw-algorithm] Leaving off the initial $C_{0}\,\theta$ term, the remainder is a summation of the appropriate form.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/clenshaw-algorithm] There is no leading term because $\phi _{0}(\theta )=\sin 0\theta =\sin 0=0$ .
[src:chebyshev-approximation/clenshaw-algorithm] Note that the algorithm requires only the evaluation of two trigonometric quantities $\cos \theta$ and $\sin \theta$ .
[src:chebyshev-approximation/clenshaw-algorithm] Sometimes it necessary to compute the difference of two meridian arcs in a way that maintains high relative accuracy.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/discrete-chebyshev-transform] Like the Chebyshev polynomials, it is named after Pafnuty Chebyshev.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/discrete-chebyshev-transform] Both of these transforms result in coefficients of Chebyshev polynomials of the first kind.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/discrete-chebyshev-transform] Other discrete Chebyshev transforms involve related grids and coefficients of Chebyshev polynomials of the second, third, or fourth kinds.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/discrete-chebyshev-transform] MATLAB's built-in `dct` (discrete cosine transform) function is implemented using the fast Fourier transform.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/discrete-chebyshev-transform] The primary uses of the discrete Chebyshev transform are numerical integration, interpolation, and stable numerical differentiation.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/discrete-chebyshev-transform] An implementation which provides these features is given in the C++ library Boost.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/equioscillation-theorem] In mathematics, the **equioscillation theorem** concerns the approximation of continuous functions using polynomials when the merit function is the maximum difference (uniform norm).
[src:chebyshev-approximation/equioscillation-theorem] Its discovery is attributed to Chebyshev.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/equioscillation-theorem] Let f be a continuous function from $[a,b]$ to $\mathbb {R}$ .
[src:chebyshev-approximation/equioscillation-theorem] That is, the polynomial g oscillates above and below f at the interpolation points, and does so to the same degree.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/equioscillation-theorem] Let us define the *equioscillation* condition as the condition in the theorem statement, that is, the condition that there exists $n+2$ ordered points in the interval such that the difference $f(x_{i})-g(x_{i})$ alternates in sign and is equal in magnitude to the uniform-norm of $f(x)-g(x)$ .
[src:chebyshev-approximation/equioscillation-theorem] We need to prove that this condition is 'sufficient' for the polynomial g being the best uniform approximation to f , and we need to prove that this condition is 'necessary' for a polynomial to be the best uniform approximation.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/equioscillation-theorem] Assume by contradiction that a polynomial $p(x)$ of degree less than or equal to n existed that provides a uniformly better approximation to f , which means that $\|f-p\|_{\infty }<\|f-g\|_{\infty }$ .
[src:chebyshev-approximation/equioscillation-theorem] is also of degree less than or equal to n .
[src:chebyshev-approximation/equioscillation-theorem] Thus, $h(x_{i})$ will also alternate sign on these $n+2$ points, and thus have at least $n+1$ roots.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/equioscillation-theorem] However, since h is a 'polynomial' of at most degree n , it should only have at most n roots.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/equioscillation-theorem] Given a polynomial g , let us define $M=\|f(x)-g(x)\|_{\infty }$ .
[src:chebyshev-approximation/equioscillation-theorem] We will call a point x an *upper point* if $f(x)-g(x)=M$ and a *lower point* if it equals $-M$ instead.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/equioscillation-theorem] Define an *alternating set* (given polynomial g and function f ) to be a set of ordered points $x_{0},...x_{n}$ in $[a,b]$ such that for every point $x_{i}$ in the alternating set, we have $f(x_{i})-g(x_{i})=\sigma (-1^{i})M$ , where $\sigma$ equals 1 or $-1$ as before.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/equioscillation-theorem] For every i , the i th alternating point $x_{i}$ is in the i th section $I_{i}$ 3.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/equioscillation-theorem] If $x_{i}$ is an upper point, then $I_{i}$ contains no lower points.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/equioscillation-theorem] Likewise, if $x_{i}$ is a lower point, then $I_{i}$ contains no upper points.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/equioscillation-theorem] Given an approximating polynomial g that does not satisfy the equioscillation condition, it is possible to show that the polynomial will have a two point alternating set.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/equioscillation-theorem] This alternating set can then be expanded to a sectioned alternating set.
[src:chebyshev-approximation/equioscillation-theorem] Several minimax approximation algorithms are available, the most common being the Remez algorithm.
